# Outline
Graphene is currently studied as reinforcing element for polymer nanocomposites – among many other applications. It is considered that its exceptional stiffness and strength should impart similar properties to the composite. However, this depends on the strength of the interface and on the state of the graphene sheets. Good interface strength requires good bonding of polymeric chains to graphene which, in turn, requires that the graphene sheets contain defects, such as vacancies and functionalization groups. How fast the properties of graphene degrade as the concentration of defects increases? To study this problem, we prepared graphene with controlled concentration of vacancies by exposing pristine graphene to oxygen plasma for specific time intervals. The concentration was evaluated, indirectly, using Raman spectroscopy after the plasma etching treatment. Then, the sheets were placed on top of a substrate with holes of known diameter (Fig. 11(b)). Mechanical testing was performed with the tip of an AFM, as shown in Fig. 11(a). Figure 11(c) shows an AFM scan of the sheet placed on top of the substrate. One can see the holes not covered by the sheet (black), while the other ones are not visible.

